{
  "answer": "**Āṅgirasa Smṛti**, **Bṛhaspati Smṛti**, **Manusmṛti**, and **Vīramitrodaya** are the primary works in the corpus that reference or invoke the Veda (or specific Vedas like the Ṛgveda, Yajurveda, or Sāmaveda) directly as authoritative sources for rituals, mantras, study rules, time, and priestly qualifications.[^1][^2][^3][^4]\n\nNo other works in the corpus yield matches for \"Veda\", its plural, or the four Vedas by name (e.g., no Atharvaveda hits). These references are typical in Dharmashastra texts, treating the Veda as the highest scriptural authority over Purāṇas or Smṛti in matters like rites and expiation.\n\n[^1]: Unknown, *Āṅgirasa Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-angirasa-smrti-2bf9d1/01/translation/#p-ed467c).\n\n[^2]: Unknown, *Bṛhaspati Smṛti*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-d19896).\n\n[^3]: Manu, *Manusmṛti*, Chapter 4, [paragraph](/works/unknown-manusmrti-347b76/04/translation/#p-b8ab54).\n\n[^4]: Mitra Miśra, *Vīramitrodaya*, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-viramitrodaya-d4b632/01/translation/#p-19342f).",
